    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### EDA Findings\n",
        "These are the findings from EDA: \n",
        "- We decided that subjects would not be a necessary attribute for this dataset and could negatively effect decisions. Due to this, we removed it from the dataset.\n",
        "- We discovered that Test_time was time since recruitment. This is related to the subjects tests and would not be necessary if we were removing subjects from the dataset. This also contained negative values which would skew our research data.\n",
        "- Through EDA, we also discovered that there were no missing values in this dataset. However, we did discover that 'sex' had 0 values, but this was okay as sex in this data set is 1 or 0. \n",
        "- Another point of interest was the amount of male subjects compared to female. We found that there was almost double the amount of males. This could be due to subject bias, which will we keep in mind.\n",
        "- From doing a pairplot, we noticed that higher RDPE leads to a higher NHR and a higher Jitter(%). In addition, higher shimmer leads to a higher NHR and a higher RDPE. This is one of the strongest corrolations we have seen and will be sure to investigate this further. \n",
        "- Finally, we noticed that some columns had outliers, such as: \n",
        "\n",
        "1. NHR\n",
        "2. HNR\n",
        "3. RDPE\n",
        "4. PPE\n",
        "5. Jitter \n",
        "6. Shimmer\n",
        "\n",
        "Outliers are always expected in large data sets, but we will be sure to keep these in mind for further investigation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aQVWx4C4YzA4"
      }
    },

    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Initialize a RobustScaler object\n",
        "robust_scaler = RobustScaler()\n",
        "# Define a list of column names with outliers\n",
        "columns_with_outliers = [\"NHR\", \"HNR\", \"RPDE\", \"PPE\",\n",
        "                         \"Jitter(%)\", \"Jitter:RAP\", \"Jitter:PPQ5\", \"Jitter:DDP\", \"Jitter(Abs)\",\n",
        "                         \"Shimmer\", \"Shimmer(dB)\", \"Shimmer:APQ3\", \"Shimmer:APQ5\", \"Shimmer:APQ11\", \"Shimmer:DDA\"]\n",
        "# Apply the RobustScaler to the specified columns in the DataFrame\n",
        "df[columns_with_outliers] = robust_scaler.fit_transform(df[columns_with_outliers])"

      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### K-Means Clustering"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0q1ti-WNi67m"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "colors = np.array(['orange', 'blue', 'lime', 'purple', 'khaki', 'pink', 'green', 'purple'])\n",
        "# Define a function that creates a scatter plot of points with different colors for each cluster\n",
        "# and optionally plots the centers of the clusters\n",
        "def clustering_scatterplot(points, labels, centers, title):\n",
        "    \n",
        "     # Get the number of clusters\n",
        "    n_clusters = np.unique(labels).size\n",
        "     # Create a scatter plot of the points, with a different color for each cluster\n",
        "    for i in range(n_clusters):\n",
        "        h = plt.scatter(points[labels==i,0],\n",
        "                        points[labels==i,1], \n",
        "                        c=colors[i%colors.size],\n",
        "                        label = 'cluster '+str(i))\n",
        "\n",
        "    # plot the centers of the clusters\n",
        "    if centers is not None:\n",
        "        plt.scatter(centers[:,0], centers[:,1], c='r', marker='*', s=500)\n",
        "  # Add a title, legend, and axis labels to the plot\n",
        "    _ = plt.title(title)\n",
        "    _ = plt.legend()\n",
        "    _ = plt.xlabel('x')\n",
        "    _ = plt.ylabel('y')"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yHrIGyQdjCEd"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
        "from sklearn import manifold\n",
        "import warnings\n",
        "warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\")\n",
        "# Convert the dataframe to a numpy array of floats\n",
        "data = np.array(df.values, dtype=float)\n",
        "for n_cluster in range(2, 11):\n",
        "   # Use the KMeans algorithm to cluster the data into n_cluster clusters\n",
        "    clustered_data_sklearn = KMeans(n_clusters=n_cluster).fit(data)\n",
        "     # Get the cluster labels for each data point\n",
        "    label = clustered_data_sklearn.labels_\n",
        "     # Calculate the silhouette score for the clustering using the Euclidean distance metric\n",
        "    sil_coeff = silhouette_score(data, label, metric='euclidean')\n",
        "    print(\"For n_clusters={}, The Silhouette Coefficient is {}\".format(n_cluster, sil_coeff))"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "a987Tvd5jPID",
        "outputId": "0bae7d40-aa96-4559-f5e6-feebd33ff832"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "For n_clusters=2, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.5211028760802132\n",
            "For n_clusters=3, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.4871977600245149\n",
            "For n_clusters=4, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.43769783436281606\n",
            "For n_clusters=5, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.4272105762312824\n",
            "For n_clusters=6, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.4126463034488072\n",
            "For n_clusters=7, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.3901365663043738\n",
            "For n_clusters=8, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.35802573704380675\n",
            "For n_clusters=9, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.34325195061595354\n",
            "For n_clusters=10, The Silhouette Coefficient is 0.31638387602493645\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The highest silhouette coefficient that we can see is 0.5211. This suggests that the ideal number of clusters to use is k=2. Due to this being closest to the bottom left, we choose to use the elbow method."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "t9WSK990kE5O"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Initialize an empty list to store the inertia values\n",
        "inertia = []\n",
        "\n",
        "for n_clusters in range(1,11):\n",
        "# Use the KMeans algorithm to cluster the data into n_clusters clusters\n",
        "    clustered_data_sklearn = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, init='k-means++', random_state=0, n_init=30, max_iter=100)\n",
        "    clustered_data_sklearn.fit(data)\n",
        "     # Append the inertia value to the inertia list\n",
        "    inertia.append(clustered_data_sklearn.inertia_)\n",
        "    \n",
        "plt.plot(range(1,11), inertia, marker='o')\n",
        "plt.title('Elbow method')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('k clusters')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('inertia')\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "    "
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 472
        },
        "id": "S_X1JIvukPBZ",
        "outputId": "d94c73b1-aab2-4396-a469-1003908743d7"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "To determine the optimal number of clusters, we have to select the value of k at the “elbow” ie the point after which the distortion/inertia start decreasing in a linear fashion. Thus for the given data, we conclude that the optimal number of clusters for the data is 2."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "T_p69pPdkjA2"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "k = 2\n",
        "clustered_data_sklearn = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k, n_init=10, max_iter=150).fit(data)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "THh0TZvHkqxm"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The next step is to append the cluster centres to the dataset"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_IpFg8FikvIO"
      }
    },

      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "data_and_centers = np.r_[data,clustered_data_sklearn.cluster_centers_]"

        "id": "Ns_WdSMwky1p"

      "outputs": []
    },

        "### Applying manifold learning techniques"

      "metadata": {
        "id": "2XsEuL1Jk2Js"
      }
    },

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "####Multi-Dimensional Scaling"

      "source": [
        "Here, we are applying multi-dimensional scaling (MDS) to project the data and the k-Means cluster centers to a 2D space."

    {

        "clustering_scatterplot(points=XYcoordinates[:-k,:], \n",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Predictive Modelling"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "BSwMrPA4ogkd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "##### Making test and train sets"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ps0GLeVWomXB"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "y = df['total_UPDRS']\n",
        "X = df.drop('total_UPDRS', axis=1).values\n",
        "\n",
        "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, shuffle=True)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "O1Yw5P5Molof"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### Grid Search for Best Parameters and Best Dimensionality Reduction Method"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "f3xvQSrnotK8"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#### Random Forest Pipeline"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "-HOhP6cnowmF"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('reduce_dim', 'passthrough'),\n",
        "                       ('regresson', RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=10))])"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "1-n-NVk3owDo"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Define the parameter grid for the grid search\n",
        "N_FEATURES_OPTIONS = [2, 6, 11]   # List of options for number of features to reduce to\n",
        "MAX_DEPTH_OPTIONS = [2, 4, 6, 8]  # List of options for maximum depth of the regression tree\n",
        "\n",
        "param_grid = [\n",
        "    {\n",
        "        'reduce_dim': [PCA(iterated_power=7)],  # Use PCA for dimensionality reduction with 7 iterations of power method\n",
        "        'reduce_dim__n_components': N_FEATURES_OPTIONS,  # Test different number of components to reduce to\n",
        "        'regresson__max_depth': MAX_DEPTH_OPTIONS  # Test different maximum depths for the regression tree\n",
        "    },\n",
        "    {\n",
        "        'reduce_dim': [RFE(svm.SVR(kernel='linear', gamma='auto')),RFE(RandomForestRegressor())],  # Use recursive feature elimination with SVM and random forest regressors\n",
        "        'reduce_dim__n_features_to_select': N_FEATURES_OPTIONS,  # Test different number of features to select\n",
        "        'regresson__max_depth': MAX_DEPTH_OPTIONS  # Test different maximum depths for the regression tree\n",
        "    }  \n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "# Use GridSearchCV to find the best combination of parameters\n",
        "search = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=5, refit=True)  # Use pipeline \"pipe\", and perform 5-fold cross validation with parallel jobs\n",
        "search.fit(X_train, y_train)  # Fit the training data to the grid search\n",
        "\n",
        "# Print the best results\n",
        "print(\"Best CV score = %0.3f:\" % search.best_score_)  # Print the best score\n",
        "print(\"Best parameters: \", search.best_params_)  # Print the best combination of parameters\n",
        "\n",
        "# Store the best parameters and model for later use\n",
        "RF_best_params = search.best_params_  # Store the best combination of parameters in a variable\n",
        "RF_best_model = search.best_estimator_  # Store the best model in a variable\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "jnMlEOFDo0wd",
        "outputId": "429785ed-68d2-494c-a600-02e266d5f81f"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Best CV score = 0.913:\n",
            "Best parameters:  {'reduce_dim': RFE(estimator=RandomForestRegressor(), n_features_to_select=11), 'reduce_dim__n_features_to_select': 11, 'regresson__max_depth': 8}\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#### Linear Regression Pipeline"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iR-YMN3ro3UD"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "pipe = Pipeline(steps=[('reduce_dim', 'passthrough'),\n",
        "                       ('regresson', LinearRegression())])"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_14J6Yroo5PV"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "N_FEATURES_OPTIONS = [2, 6, 11]\n",
        "NORMALIZE_OPTIONS = [False, True]\n",
        "\n",
        "param_grid = [    {        'reduce_dim': [PCA(iterated_power=7)],\n",
        "        'reduce_dim__n_components': N_FEATURES_OPTIONS,\n",
        "    },\n",
        "    {\n",
        "        'reduce_dim': [RFE(svm.SVR(kernel='linear', gamma='auto')), RFE(LinearRegression())],\n",
        "        'reduce_dim__n_features_to_select': N_FEATURES_OPTIONS,\n",
        "    }  \n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "pipe = Pipeline([\n",
        "    ('reduce_dim', None),\n",
        "    ('regressor', LinearRegression())\n",
        "])\n",
        "\n",
        "search = GridSearchCV(pipe, param_grid, n_jobs=-1, cv=5, refit=True)\n",
        "search.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "print(\"Best CV score = %0.3f:\" % search.best_score_)\n",
        "print(\"Best parameters: \", search.best_params_)\n",
        "\n",
        "# store the best params and best model for later use\n",

    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### Compare Regression Models on Test Set"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2X7uJqj5vnTK"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# model - a trained regression model\n",
        "\n",
        "def evaluate_model(X_test, y_test, model):\n",
        "    \n",
        "    # compute prediction for the test set\n",
        "    _predicted_values = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "        \n",
        "    # compute metrics\n",
        "    _mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, _predicted_values)\n",
        "    _mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, _predicted_values)\n",
        "    _r2 = r2_score(y_test, _predicted_values)\n",
        "    _acc = model.score(X_test, y_test)\n",
        "            \n",
        "    return _mse, _mae, _r2, _acc"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iGz0sfcKvrvr"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "RF_mse, RF_mae, RF_r2, RF_acc = evaluate_model(X_test, y_test, RF_best_model)# Evaluate the random forest model on the test set and store the performance metrics in variables\n",
        "LR_mse, LR_mae, LR_r2, LR_acc = evaluate_model(X_test, y_test, LR_best_model)# Evaluate the linear regression model on the test set and store the performance metrics in variables\n",
        "SGD_mse, SGD_mae, SGD_r2, SGD_acc = evaluate_model(X_test, y_test, SGD_best_model)# Evaluate the stochastic gradient descent model on the test set and store the performance metrics in variables"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "b8CDQHpbvuUB"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",

        "#Create a dataframe for mean squared error (MSE) values for each model\n",
        "df_mse = pd.DataFrame({'Random Forest': RF_mse, 'Linear Regression': LR_mse, 'SGD Regressor': SGD_mse}, index=['MSE'])\n",
        "#Create a dataframe for mean absolute error (MAE) values for each model\n",
        "df_mae = pd.DataFrame({'Random Forest': RF_mae, 'Linear Regression': LR_mae, 'SGD Regressor': SGD_mae}, index=['MAE'])\n",
        "#Create a dataframe for R-squared (R2) values for each model\n",
        "df_r2 = pd.DataFrame({'Random Forest': RF_r2, 'Linear Regression': LR_r2, 'SGD Regressor': SGD_r2}, index=['R2'])\n",
        "df_acc = pd.DataFrame({'Random Forest': RF_acc, 'Linear Regression': LR_acc, 'SGD Regressor': SGD_acc}, index=['Accuracy'])\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=4, figsize=(20, 5))\n",

      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "## Predictive Modelling Findings\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VJ9Pyw7twSCl"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "The analysis performed on the different regression models found that Random Forest had the lowest Mean Squared Error (MSE), which is a metric that measures the average squared difference between the predicted and actual values. This indicates that Random Forest is the most accurate model in predicting the outcome variable. Additionally, the Mean Absolute Error (MAE), which measures the average absolute difference between the predicted and actual values, was also much lower for Random Forest compared to the other two models.\n",
        "\n",
        "The R-squared (R2) value was much higher for Random Forest compared to the other two models, indicating that Random Forest explains a higher amount of variability in the outcome variable. This suggests that the model captures the relationship between the predictor variables and the outcome variable more effectively.\n",
        "\n",
        "Furthermore, the accuracy of Random Forest was significantly higher than the other two models, indicating that it is the most effective in classifying the data points into their corresponding classes. The high accuracy of the model was further supported by the high CV_Score, which measures the model's performance on cross-validation.\n",
        "\n",
        "We used Random Forest as our final model to predict total_UPDRS on X_test data set. We compared it to Y_test set which had total_UPDRS. Our model is highly accurate with a correlation of 0.96 between actual total_UPDRS and Prediction. The closer the correlation is to one, the more accurate the model is. This proves that our model is highly accurate.\n",
        "\n",
        "Random Forest is a good regression learning method due to its robustness, non-parametric nature, feature importance, scalability, and high accuracy in handling complex data."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_JelzdGvwUw4"
      }

  ]
}
